#: ../../../release/1.4.0-notes.rst:3
msgid "NumPy 1.4.0 Release Notes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.4.0-notes.rst:5
msgid ""
"This minor includes numerous bug fixes, as well as a few new features. It is "
"backward compatible with 1.3.0 release."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.4.0-notes.rst:9
msgid "Highlights"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.4.0-notes.rst:11
msgid "New datetime dtype support to deal with dates in arrays"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.4.0-notes.rst:13
msgid "Faster import time"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.4.0-notes.rst:15 ../../../release/1.4.0-notes.rst:25
msgid "Extended array wrapping mechanism for ufuncs"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.4.0-notes.rst:17
msgid "New Neighborhood iterator (C-level only)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.4.0-notes.rst:19
msgid "C99-like complex functions in npymath"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.4.0-notes.rst:22
msgid "New features"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.4.0-notes.rst:27
msgid ""
"An __array_prepare__ method has been added to ndarray to provide subclasses "
"greater flexibility to interact with ufuncs and ufunc-like functions. "
"ndarray already provided __array_wrap__, which allowed subclasses to set the "
"array type for the result and populate metadata on the way out of the ufunc "
"(as seen in the implementation of MaskedArray). For some applications it is "
"necessary to provide checks and populate metadata *on the way in*. "
"__array_prepare__ is therefore called just after the ufunc has initialized "
"the output array but before computing the results and populating it. This "
"way, checks can be made and errors raised before operations which may modify "
"data in place."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.4.0-notes.rst:38
msgid "Automatic detection of forward incompatibilities"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.4.0-notes.rst:40
msgid ""
"Previously, if an extension was built against a version N of NumPy, and used "
"on a system with NumPy M < N, the import_array was successful, which could "
"cause crashes because the version M does not have a function in N. Starting "
"from NumPy 1.4.0, this will cause a failure in import_array, so the error "
"will be caught early on."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.4.0-notes.rst:47
msgid "New iterators"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.4.0-notes.rst:49
msgid ""
"A new neighborhood iterator has been added to the C API. It can be used to "
"iterate over the items in a neighborhood of an array, and can handle "
"boundaries conditions automatically. Zero and one padding are available, as "
"well as arbitrary constant value, mirror and circular padding."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.4.0-notes.rst:55
msgid "New polynomial support"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.4.0-notes.rst:57
msgid ""
"New modules chebyshev and polynomial have been added. The new polynomial "
"module is not compatible with the current polynomial support in numpy, but "
"is much like the new chebyshev module. The most noticeable difference to "
"most will be that coefficients are specified from low to high power, that "
"the low level functions do *not* work with the Chebyshev and Polynomial "
"classes as arguments, and that the Chebyshev and Polynomial classes include "
"a domain. Mapping between domains is a linear substitution and the two "
"classes can be converted one to the other, allowing, for instance, a "
"Chebyshev series in one domain to be expanded as a polynomial in another "
"domain. The new classes should generally be used instead of the low level "
"functions, the latter are provided for those who wish to build their own "
"classes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.4.0-notes.rst:69
msgid ""
"The new modules are not automatically imported into the numpy namespace, "
"they must be explicitly brought in with an \"import numpy.polynomial\" "
"statement."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.4.0-notes.rst:74
msgid "New C API"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.4.0-notes.rst:76
msgid "The following C functions have been added to the C API:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.4.0-notes.rst:78
msgid ""
"PyArray_GetNDArrayCFeatureVersion: return the *API* version of the loaded "
"numpy."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.4.0-notes.rst:80
msgid ""
"PyArray_Correlate2 - like PyArray_Correlate, but implements the usual "
"definition of correlation. Inputs are not swapped, and conjugate is taken "
"for complex arrays."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.4.0-notes.rst:83
msgid ""
"PyArray_NeighborhoodIterNew - a new iterator to iterate over a neighborhood "
"of a point, with automatic boundaries handling. It is documented in the "
"iterators section of the C-API reference, and you can find some examples in  "
"the multiarray_test.c.src file in numpy.core."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.4.0-notes.rst:89
msgid "New ufuncs"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.4.0-notes.rst:91
msgid "The following ufuncs have been added to the C API:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.4.0-notes.rst:93
msgid ""
"copysign - return the value of the first argument with the sign copied from "
"the second argument."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.4.0-notes.rst:95
msgid ""
"nextafter - return the next representable floating point value of the first "
"argument toward the second argument."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.4.0-notes.rst:99
msgid "New defines"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.4.0-notes.rst:101
msgid ""
"The alpha processor is now defined and available in numpy/npy_cpu.h. The "
"failed detection of the PARISC processor has been fixed. The defines are:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.4.0-notes.rst:104
msgid "NPY_CPU_HPPA: PARISC"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.4.0-notes.rst:105
msgid "NPY_CPU_ALPHA: Alpha"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.4.0-notes.rst:108
msgid "Testing"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.4.0-notes.rst:110
msgid ""
"deprecated decorator: this decorator may be used to avoid cluttering testing "
"output while testing DeprecationWarning is effectively raised by the "
"decorated test."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.4.0-notes.rst:113
msgid ""
"assert_array_almost_equal_nulp: new method to compare two arrays of floating "
"point values. With this function, two values are considered close if there "
"are not many representable floating point values in between, thus being more "
"robust than assert_array_almost_equal when the values fluctuate a lot."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.4.0-notes.rst:118
msgid ""
"assert_array_max_ulp: raise an assertion if there are more than N "
"representable numbers between two floating point values."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.4.0-notes.rst:120
msgid ""
"assert_warns: raise an AssertionError if a callable does not generate a "
"warning of the appropriate class, without altering the warning state."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.4.0-notes.rst:124
msgid "Reusing npymath"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.4.0-notes.rst:126
msgid ""
"In 1.3.0, we started putting portable C math routines in npymath library, so "
"that people can use those to write portable extensions. Unfortunately, it "
"was not possible to easily link against this library: in 1.4.0, support has "
"been added to numpy.distutils so that 3rd party can reuse this library. See "
"coremath documentation for more information."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.4.0-notes.rst:133
msgid "Improved set operations"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.4.0-notes.rst:135
msgid ""
"In previous versions of NumPy some set functions (intersect1d, setxor1d, "
"setdiff1d and setmember1d) could return incorrect results if the input "
"arrays contained duplicate items. These now work correctly for input arrays "
"with duplicates. setmember1d has been renamed to in1d, as with the change to "
"accept arrays with duplicates it is no longer a set operation, and is "
"conceptually similar to an elementwise version of the Python operator 'in'.  "
"All of these functions now accept the boolean keyword assume_unique. This is "
"False by default, but can be set True if the input arrays are known not to "
"contain duplicates, which can increase the functions' execution speed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.4.0-notes.rst:148
msgid "Improvements"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.4.0-notes.rst:150
msgid ""
"numpy import is noticeably faster (from 20 to 30 % depending on the platform "
"and computer)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.4.0-notes.rst:153
msgid "The sort functions now sort nans to the end."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.4.0-notes.rst:155
msgid "Real sort order is [R, nan]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.4.0-notes.rst:156
msgid "Complex sort order is [R + Rj, R + nanj, nan + Rj, nan + nanj]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.4.0-notes.rst:158
msgid ""
"Complex numbers with the same nan placements are sorted according to the non-"
"nan part if it exists."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.4.0-notes.rst:160
msgid ""
"The type comparison functions have been made consistent with the new sort "
"order of nans. Searchsorted now works with sorted arrays containing nan "
"values."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.4.0-notes.rst:163
msgid "Complex division has been made more resistant to overflow."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.4.0-notes.rst:164
msgid "Complex floor division has been made more resistant to overflow."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.4.0-notes.rst:167
msgid "Deprecations"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.4.0-notes.rst:169
msgid "The following functions are deprecated:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.4.0-notes.rst:171
msgid ""
"correlate: it takes a new keyword argument old_behavior. When True (the "
"default), it returns the same result as before. When False, compute the "
"conventional correlation, and take the conjugate for complex arrays. The old "
"behavior will be removed in NumPy 1.5, and raises a DeprecationWarning in "
"1.4."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.4.0-notes.rst:177
msgid ""
"unique1d: use unique instead. unique1d raises a deprecation warning in 1.4, "
"and will be removed in 1.5."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.4.0-notes.rst:180
msgid ""
"intersect1d_nu: use intersect1d instead. intersect1d_nu raises a deprecation "
"warning in 1.4, and will be removed in 1.5."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.4.0-notes.rst:183
msgid ""
"setmember1d: use in1d instead. setmember1d raises a deprecation warning in "
"1.4, and will be removed in 1.5."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.4.0-notes.rst:186
msgid "The following raise errors:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.4.0-notes.rst:188
msgid ""
"When operating on 0-d arrays, ``numpy.max`` and other functions accept only "
"``axis=0``, ``axis=-1`` and ``axis=None``. Using an out-of-bounds axes is an "
"indication of a bug, so Numpy raises an error for these cases now."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.4.0-notes.rst:193
msgid ""
"Specifying ``axis > MAX_DIMS`` is no longer allowed; Numpy raises now an "
"error instead of behaving similarly as for ``axis=None``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.4.0-notes.rst:197
msgid "Internal changes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.4.0-notes.rst:200
msgid "Use C99 complex functions when available"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.4.0-notes.rst:202
msgid ""
"The numpy complex types are now guaranteed to be ABI compatible with C99 "
"complex type, if available on the platform. Moreover, the complex ufunc now "
"use the platform C99 functions instead of our own."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.4.0-notes.rst:207
msgid "split multiarray and umath source code"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.4.0-notes.rst:209
msgid ""
"The source code of multiarray and umath has been split into separate logic "
"compilation units. This should make the source code more amenable for "
"newcomers."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.4.0-notes.rst:214
msgid "Separate compilation"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.4.0-notes.rst:216
msgid ""
"By default, every file of multiarray (and umath) is merged into one for "
"compilation as was the case before, but if NPY_SEPARATE_COMPILATION env "
"variable is set to a non-negative value, experimental individual compilation "
"of each file is enabled. This makes the compile/debug cycle much faster when "
"working on core numpy."
msgstr ""

